<h1><%= @operator.name %></h1>
<div style="float:<% if @operator.role == 'Defender' %>right<% else %>left<% end %>;" class="img">
  <img id="op" src="/assets/small-<%= @operator.name %>.png" alt="">
</div>


<div class="genInfo" style="float:<% if @operator.role == 'Defender' %>right<% else %>left<% end %>;">
  <p>
    <strong>Pick rate:</strong>
    <%= @operator.pick_rate %>
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Win rate:</strong>
    <%= @operator.win_rate %>
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Guns:</strong>
    <% @guns.each do |gun| %>
      <% if gun.operators.detect{|o| o.name == @operator.name} %>
        <%= link_to gun.name, gun_path(gun.id) %>
      <% end %>
    <% end %>
  </p>
  <% if @operator.name == "Thermite" %>
    <h3>General Tips</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Thermite is a reinforced breacher, giving him a VIP status on the team. If Thermite dies, you are almost guaranteed to lose the match due to being the only person who can breach. This is slightly less so if you have a Hibana however.</li>
      <li>Due to his role on the team, he is played very support centric until he can move up with his team to breach by holding angles, droning out for his fraggers, and just doing his best to not die.</li>
      <li>On bomb, he has a secondary purpose in that he can plant defuser due to being able to take smokes in his loadout. With this it is important to learn the best spots to plant defuser (will be added in the future).</li>
      <li>Both of his secondary gadgets are good takes. Smokes have the use of covering lines of sight to cross over, allowing Glaz to shoot all his moving bananas safely, and blocking sight when going to plant. His claymore can be very good for both defending against peakers and run outs early on in the push and defending flanks or protecting defuser after it has been planted. The choice is based on preference so take what you feel you like more and works best.</li>
      <li><em>Save your drone!</em> As stated before, you are going to be a much more supportive operator early on and having both your drones is a great help.</li>
      <li><em>Always have a Thatcher or Twitch.</em> They are the two operators who will help get rid of Bandit's batteries or Mute's jammers. You can do it yourself from above but it is easier to just have them do it.</li>
      <li><em>Know about Bandit Trick.</em> If you don't know what it is, you can find it <a href="/operators/24">here</a> for a more in-depth look. What it is briefly though is Bandit is able to electrify a reinforcement as you are placing your charge. Be aware and listen!</li>
    </ul>
  <% elsif @operator.name == "Ash" %>
    <ul>
      <li>Ash is a play maker and if you plan to play her, don't be scared to try and make them. If you know someone is in a room, go around a back door or from above and rush in. Just be confident and take risks on her.</li>
      <li>Use your gadgets. Use them all effectively which will be learned over time but if you die with something on you, it's less useful than if they were used to try to get things done. This includes flashbangs, breaching charge, Ash round, etc.</li>
      <li>You may be on a good solo operator/roam clearer but play with your team at all times. If you hear that someone is in a room and you may be close, think of how you can be useful to the team in this situation. But never ever do you only play on your own and ignore team call outs as that will only be detrimental to the team as a whole.</li>
    </ul>
  <% elsif @operator.name == "Castle" %>
    <ul>
      <li>Castle has shield trick the same way we have Bandit trick. Shield trick is when you put a deployable shield just outside so that you can still put your baricade up, making it harder to break down the baricade and get in the room unless they have an Ash.</li>
      <li>If a teammate breaks down one of your baricades, you can replace it after. You do not lose your baricades unless they are destroyed.</li>
      <li>Don't reinforce doors until your team has gone where they need to go because they will just break it down and you will have wasted time.</li>
      <li>Be careful if they have a Fuze as you won't be able to shoot him as he places his charge but he'll have real fun time bombing you and your team.</li>
      <li>Your baricades take 12 melees to take down, which allows for Castle tricking where you melee the baricade 11 times and when you hear a Fuze or something on the baricade, melee it and shoot them as it's not something people expect.</li>
      <li>Mute works incredibly well with Castle. Mute jammers can defend your baricades which would require a Twitch or Thatcher to be able to get past that. If done correctly, it'll be near impossible to get in unless there is a Sledge.</li>
    </ul>
  <% elsif @operator.name == "Pulse" %>
  <% elsif @operator.name == "Twitch" %>
    <h3>General Tips</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>The most important tip is <strong>DO NOT</strong> go to the objective room with your drone during prep phase. This is an almost guaranteed way to lose your drone. Use this time instead to take out cameras throughout the map.</li>
      <li>Don't zap people. This is another way to lose your drone. Only do it to kill an AFK or DBNO enemy or to set up a kill for your team by distracting the opponent.</li>
      <li>Go into objective only after prep phase as a way to destroy enemy gadgets such as Bandit batteries, Mute jammers, and Mira's windows (which can be shot out by the drone.)</li>
      <li>Consider your drone your life. If you lose them both, all you are is another gun so protect them well throughout the match.</li>
      <li>Your drone cannot jump. That would be terrifying if it could jump and shock people. But due to this, you need to make sure to stick to walls with lots of drone holes or stick to areas with lots of cover.</li>
      <li>A less important tip but still good to know. Consider taking laser sights on the F2 as the spread is good already and this just makes it better while going from hip fire to ADS.</li>
    </ul>
  <% elsif @operator.name == "Doc" %>
    <h3>General Tips</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>There are three playstyles to Doc: Aggro Doc which is very heavy on peaking and trading damage, then healing himself back up after, Defensive Doc who uses his overheal at the end of a round when attackers are likely to try to get to the point or when a rush is coming, and Passive Doc who heals during the round after a teammate or himself takes lots of damage. A good Doc knows how to switch between these throughout the round.</li>
      <li>Although Aggro Doc is a thing, that doesn't mean to wildly peak. Be smart and peek when it's safe.</li>
      <li>Your healing darts have dropoff and don't fire as straight. Keep this in mind when going to shoot a teammate.</li>
      <li>Your gadget can heal teammates, remember that. Just don't heal anyone if they only took 10 damage or so, save it for anything over 30 damage.</li>
      <li>The med gun can instant revive a downed hostage or teammate from range. Use it to your advantage.</li>
      <li>Don't remove your hands from the keyboard and mouse/controller as you can revive yourself when downed to get back into the fight.</li>
      <li>Don't use your heal to only heal hurt allies. Use it for overhealing when the other team is pushing as it will give an edge in combat. As well, don't overheal at the start of a round as the overheal doesn't last forever.</li>
      <li>If you can have a Rook on the team, Doc works very well with him as his armor can help a person survive longer and having Doc overheal just makes a person last even more.</li>
    </ul>
  <%elsif @operator.name == "Rook" %>
    <h3>General Tips</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Always, always, ALWAYS put your armor down as soon as you spawn.</li>
      <li>Remind your team at all times to pick up the armor.</li>
      <li>Do not destroy your armor. If someone gets downed, you can pick up another one if some are left over.</li>
      <li>Rook does very well with Doc. Between your armor and his overheal, you can keep people aliver for a very long time.</li>
      <li>For people slightly more comfortable, you can take his shotgun and can use it to make a hole above a well used entrance. This way you can watch from above and killing people without them seeing you.</li>
      <li>Use your impact grenades as a way of making rotation holes between bombs or when you want to play vertically as they are good for creating holes in breakable surfaces.</li>
    </ul>
  <% end %>
</div>

<div class="tipsInfo" style="clear:<% if @operator.role == 'Defender' %>right<% else %>left<% end %>;">
<% if @operator.name == "Thermite" %>
  <h3>Loadout</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><u><a href="/guns/4">556xi</a></u>: This is Thermite's go-to gun for the most part. It has excellent recoil, good per bullet damage, though has a lower rate of fire, making it a great distance weapon which fits into his playstyle very well.</li>
    <li><u><a href="/guns/43">M1014</a></u>: This is a semi-auto shotgun carried by FBI SWAT. This gun is only useful at close range so it's not recommended to take it unless you are playing rush Thermite.</li>
    <li><u><a href="/guns/38">M45 MEUSOC</a></u>: A solid pistol with high per bullet damage and little recoil with a muzzle break on. This gun is great for killing a downed enemy in one shot and quick switching to it if the enemy is only a shot or two away from dying and your primary is empty. However, you will find this gun lacking in extended fights.</li>
    <li><u><a href="/guns/44">5.7 USG</a></u>: Another solid pistol. It has less damage than the M45 but has the highest mag size in the game at 21. This should be taken if you are incredibly confident at your ability to hit headshots.</li>
    <li><u>Smoke Greanades</u>: As mentioned before, both gadgets are great and useful. Smokes are good for covering lines of sight on a push, covering a defuser plant, and the small added bonus of allowing Glaz to go banana hunting.</li>
    <li><u>Claymore</u>: This is a great tool to take when you want to cover flanks and run out locations. Along with this, it has the added utility of being able to protect a defuser if an enemy isn't careful.</li>
  </ul>
  <% elsif @operator.name == "Ash" %>
  <h3>Loadout</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><u><a href="/guns/1">R4-C</a></u>: Of all of Ash's guns, this has the fastest time to kill. With high damage and high rate of fire, the gun has very high recoil so it is the best gun to run if you are more comfortable with recoil control as body shots will eat through anyone.</li>
    <li><u><a href="/guns/31">G36C</a></u>: The slower of Ash's primaries, it is best for taking things slower but also being a headhunter due to how accurate the gun can be. This is recommended for people who want to take long ranged engagements.</li>
    <li><u><a href="/guns/38">M45 MEUSOC</a></u>: A solid pistol with high per bullet damage and little recoil with a muzzle break on. This gun is great for killing a downed enemy in one shot and quick switching to it if the enemy is only a shot or two away from dying and your primary is empty. However, you will find this gun lacking in extended fights.</li>
    <li><u><a href="/guns/44">5.7 USG</a></u>: Another solid pistol. It has less damage than the M45 but has the highest mag size in the game at 21. This should be taken if you are incredibly confident at your ability to hit headshots.</li>
    <li><u>Flashbangs</u>: Possibly the best gadget to go on Ash, it allows her to rush in and control the fight, then repositioning before the effect has ended.</li>
    <li><u>Breach Charges</u>: Not really as beneficial due to her gadget, you can take this in case your team is severely lacking on the breaching side.</li>
  </ul>
